I am usually a reader of the forums and do not post often.  Kethuvim can tell you that we have had many &quot;discussions&quot; about the topics in the forums, but I never post them.<br>
<br>
I have to say that I may disagree with Mork on some issues, but I can see that we have the same love and feelings about history.  Mork, I must say that I agree with all of the above posts.  Fest, I agree with you, it was not an &quot;unanimous&quot; decision.  <br>
<br>
I am from Louisiana, and am surrounded by people who could care less about those in bondage at the time of the Civil War.  I have always believed that the South had a right to leave the USA if the states so chose to.  That is not saying that I believe that slavery was a just cause to leave, but the ELECTED leaders of the southern states voted to leave.  I know that some southerners did not want to leave the US, as did all of those enslaved.  But I do feel that a vast majority of southerners did approve of the act of succession.  As a matter of fact Louisiana was the headquarters to the populist movement and they did not support either slavery or succession.  Even as this group was large in Louisiana, it was still a very minority party in the state and south as a whole.<br>
<br>
To be clear, I am saying that I support the act of self determination by states and NOT defending the act of owning/trading in human flesh.  The idea of slavery truly disturbs me.<br>
<br>
So Mork, I am with ya 100%<br>
<br>
