 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#666699><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub79.ezboard.com/umorkenlar.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Morkenlar</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Councilman</span><br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(5/24/02 6:36:24 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub79.ezboard.com/finfinitusvindicatfrm9.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=17.topic&index=14>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: The War of Northern Agression (aka Civil War)</span><hr size=1> A few things:<br>
<br>
It's much easier to &quot;fix&quot; a system as its being made, compared to after its in place.<br>
<br>
The electoral college doesn't &quot;prevent&quot; what I describe, but does make it more difficult, because more people are involved.  The more automated something is, the easier it is to take control of.  Heres an easy example: most people that bother with anti virus have their software scheduled to do scans at off hours(automating it), and then completely forget/neglect to worry about it anymore.  Now, assuming you don't control physical access to your computer very well (most people don't - I could probably get into most of your computers in under 5 mins), all it would take would be someone to modify something to interfere with the automation.  A new virus, custom made to avoid your automation - say, it alters the time on your machine right before the antivirus software is supposed to start, and resets it 10 mins later to the correct time.  Voila - your computer is now wide open to attacks, yet you have no clue, and think you are secure, because you use antivirus software.<br>
<br>
Next, the comparison with banks.  I think everyone can agree that people will, in general, put forth more effort and take more risks for a greater reward.  A few million dollars is NOTHING compared to what could be done if we automated all our voting.  Reasons people would put forth more effort:<br>
1.  Power motivates people more than money.<br>
2.  Power can give money.  Imagine the TRILLIONS of dollars that could/would be gotten, from manipulation of legalities, taxation, and high dollar industries (automotive, power, etc)<br>
3.  Even &quot;good&quot; people would probably try this - using the &quot;ends justify the means&quot; as their justification.<br>
<br>
And, as for the people breaking into banks - that HAS happened.  The reasons all the safeguards are in place now, is because they had so many problems with that initially.  Imagine the level of power that would be in the hands of the first people to exploit holes in the security.  If they planned adequately, they could abuse it in such a way as to not be punishable.  Remember, we're talking about people making laws.  First law to make - create a new class of citizen, said class being above criminal penalties.  Join said class.  Wow - now, even if they catch you, they can't do anything to you, because the laws say they can't.  How do you stop them now, without violating laws?  <br>
